  "summary_text": "Chief Complaint\nLeft knee pain following a fall while running with her niece.\n\nHistory of Present Illness\nThe patient reports that she injured her left knee while running with her niece, who was learning to ride a bike. She fell and believes she twisted her knee in an unusual way approximately one week ago. Since the injury, she has experienced limping and has been unable to bear weight fully on the left leg. The pain initially rated as a 'four' but has progressed to a 'throbbing' sensation, now rated as a 'four' and potentially worsening. She has been taking Tylenol for the pain, but it provides only temporary relief. She also took an ulcer medication recently, which precludes the use of ibuprofen. She reports using kinesiology tape for support. The patient describes the pain as being more pronounced on the medial aspect of the knee and less so on the lateral aspect.\n\nFindings\nPhysical examination reveals moderate edema and effusion in the left knee. Range of motion is limited, with pain on flexion and extension. Lachman's and valgus/varus tests are negative. A chest x-ray was performed and revealed no fractures or bony abnormalities. The patient's vital signs are stable.\n\nAssessment\nBased on the patient's history and physical examination, she likely has an MCL strain.\n\nPlan\nI am prescribing tramadol 50mg twice daily as needed for breakthrough pain, along with Tylenol as needed. I am also recommending a knee immobilizer for one week to reduce inflammation and promote healing. The patient should ice the knee three to four times a day for 20-30 minutes. I advise against running for approximately three weeks to allow the ligament to heal. I will schedule a follow-up appointment in approximately one month to reassess her condition and determine if further imaging, such as an MRI, is necessary. 't include markdown, code fences, or prefatory text. 't include markdown, code fences, or prefatory text. 't include markdown, code fences, or prefatory text. 't include markdown, code fences, or prefatory text. 't include markdown, code fences, or prefatory text. 't include markdown, code fences, or prefatory text. 't include markdown, code fences, or prefatory text.",
  "reference_summary": "HISTORY OF PRESENT ILLNESS\n\nAngela Powell is a pleasant 81-year-old female who presents to the clinic today for the evaluation of left knee pain. The onset of her pain began 1 week ago, when she was running around with her niece and fell. At the time of the injury, she heard a pop and believes that she twisted her knee. She reports that she has been limping since the injury. The patient locates her pain to the medial and lateral aspects of her knee. She rates her pain level as a 4 out of 10, however this is increasing. Her pain is described as a throbbing pain. The patient has been taking Tylenol, which has provided mild and temporary relief, as well as wrapping her knee with kinesiology tape. She states that she is unable to take ibuprofen secondary to an ulcer.\n\nPHYSICAL EXAM\n\nMSK: Examination of the left knee: Edema and effusion noted. Moderate ROM. Pain with flexion and extension of the knee. Negative Lachman's. Negative valgus and varus stress test.\n\nRESULTS\n\n4 views of the left knee were taken. These reveal no evidence of any fractures or dislocations. No other abnormalities are noted.\n\nASSESSMENT\n\nLeft knee pain, possible MCL strain.\n\nPLAN\n\nAfter reviewing the patient's examination and radiographic findings today, I have discussed with the patient that her x-rays did not reveal any signs of a tear. I have recommended that we treat the patient conservatively. The plan is to place the patient in a knee immobilizer to provide increased support for the next week. I have also prescribed the patient tramadol 50 mg to treat her pain. She can take Tylenol as needed for breakthrough pain. I have also advised her to ice her left knee 3 to 4 times a day for 20 to 30 minutes at a time. I have advised her to refrain from running for the next 3 weeks. If her pain does not improve with the immobilizer, I will recommend obtaining an MRI.",
